        "type": "Function",
        "tags": [],
        "label": "ContentEditorKibanaProvider",
        "description": [
          "\nKibana-specific Provider that maps to known dependency types.\n\nSelf-provides every external context the editor needs so consumers can drop\nit into any provider tree without thinking about ancestry:\n\n- ",
          {
            "pluginId": "@kbn/content-management-content-editor",
            "scope": "public",
            "docId": "kibKbnContentManagementContentEditorPluginApi",
            "section": "def-public.QueryClientProvider",
            "text": "QueryClientProvider"
          },
          " — the inner body uses `useQueryClient()` to\n  forward the client into the system flyout it opens, so user-profile\n  queries inside the flyout work without an outer `QueryClientProvider`.\n- ",
          {
            "pluginId": "@kbn/content-management-content-editor",
            "scope": "public",
            "docId": "kibKbnContentManagementContentEditorPluginApi",
            "section": "def-public.UserProfilesKibanaProvider",
            "text": "UserProfilesKibanaProvider"
          },
          " — the inner body reads profile services\n  via `useUserProfilesServices()` for the same forwarding reason.\n\nWhen this provider is itself rendered under another `QueryClientProvider`\nor `UserProfilesProvider` (e.g. legacy `TableListViewKibanaProvider`), the\ninner providers shadow the outer with semantically equivalent values derived\nfrom the same `core` services, so nesting is harmless."
        ],
        "signature": [
          "({ children, ...services }: React.PropsWithChildren<",
          "ContentEditorKibanaDependencies",
          ">) => React.JSX.Element"
        ],
